collapse. Œ≥c and Œ≤c are two parameters to control the mean and variance of the normalization, which
are learned by the model for each class. We use hinge loss for the adversarial training. Notice that the
proposed framework is Ô¨Çexible with different generative models, and we also show the effectiveness
of using DCGAN (Radford et al., 2015) in the supplementary."
FRAMEWORK AND ARCHITECTURE,0.187683284457478,"ReÔ¨Ånement Network (R): As one of our key contributions, we introduce the reÔ¨Ånement network
R to further reÔ¨Åne the shared representation using the global scene category labels. R takes the
predictions of the multi-task network as input and predicts the category label of the input image.
Importantly, because R only requires category labels, it can be effortlessly operationalized on the
‚Äúweakly-annotated‚Äù synthesized images. Meanwhile, R also enforces the semantic consistency of the
synthesized images with G."
FRAMEWORK AND ARCHITECTURE,0.1906158357771261,"We apply an algorithm inspired by Expectation-Maximum (EM) (Dempster et al., 1977) to train the
reÔ¨Ånement network R. For the fully-annotated real images (x, y, c), we use the scene classiÔ¨Åcation
loss to update R and reÔ¨Åne the encoder E in the multi-task network M. Then for the synthesized
images (ex, ec), since their multi-task predictions produced by M might not be reliable, we only reÔ¨Åne
E with R frozen using the scene classiÔ¨Åcation loss. Through reÔ¨Åning the share feature representation
with the synthesized images, this process also provides implicit guidance to the image generation
network."
