REFERENCES,0.8621700879765396,"D.3
EXPERIMENTS ON HIGHER IMAGE RESOLUTION"
REFERENCES,0.8651026392961877,"In principle, the proposed framework is agnostic to the speciÔ¨Åc types of multi-task networks and
image generation networks, thus Ô¨Çexible with image resolutions. The practical constraint lies in
that it is still challenging and resource-consuming for modern generative models to synthesize very
high-resolution images (Zhang et al., 2019; Brock et al., 2018), although the deep multi-task models
normally work better with high-resolution images. In the main experiments, consistent with exiting
image synthesis work (Zhang et al., 2019), we focused on the resolution of 128 √ó 128. Here we
further made an attempt to run our experiments with a higher resolution, 256 √ó 256 on NYUv2. The
results of all the compared models in the 50% data setting are shown in Table 10. We could Ô¨Ånd that
MGM still consistently outperforms the baselines, indicating the great robustness and Ô¨Çexibility of
our proposed framework."
REFERENCES,0.8680351906158358,"D.4
GENERALIZATION OF THE SHARED FEATURE REPRESENTATION"
REFERENCES,0.8709677419354839,"Intuitively, our MGM achieves state-of-the-art performance by effectively learning a shared feature
representation. We further show the generalization capability of this representation by designing the
following experiment: for the multi-task model and our MGM model, we Ô¨Årst learn the shared feature
space with the SS and DE tasks, and we then use that learned feature space to train a new decoder for
the SN task. We report the results on NYUv2 in Table 11. Our MGM outperforms the multi-task
model in all the three data settings, which means that MGM indeed learns a better and robust shared
feature space."
REFERENCES,0.873900293255132,"D.5
EXPERIMENTAL RESULTS WITH DCGAN"
REFERENCES,0.8768328445747801,"The proposed MGM model is a general framework and is Ô¨Çexible with different choices of model
components. Here we show its Ô¨Çexibility for the image generation network: We replace SAGAN
with DCGAN (Radford et al., 2015), and Table 12 shows the result on the NYUv2 dataset in the
50% data setting. Similar to the results in the main paper, MGM equipped with DCGAN (‚ÄòMGM-
DCGAN‚Äô) consistently improves the performance on all the tasks, which indicates the robustness
of the proposed MGM framework. In addition, we Ô¨Ånd that ‚ÄòMGM-SAGAN‚Äô outperforms ‚ÄòMGM-
DCGAN‚Äô, suggesting that a more powerful image generation network leads to better performance."
